<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-707-278  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 707 278.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 6 1990 v24 n32 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Packing your data in - and fast. (new storage technology promisesincredible retrieval speed and space-saving ability)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pastore, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at Microelectronics and Computer Technology Corp areapplying holographic techniques to create a new generation ofcomputer data storage that could potentially yield access speedsthat are 100 times greater than those of magnetic disk drives.andO;Holographic storage uses lasers to record data on light-sensitivecrystals that can transfer information at rates of 100M-bps to800M-bps since data is stored and retrieved in pages of up to100,000 bits rather than one bit at a time.andP;  The company hopes tobring the high price of holographic storage down to twice that ofcomparable magnetic or optical devices by 1995.andP;  Microelectronicsestimates that prices for quantity prototype units will cost$4,000 per 2Gbytes of storage capacity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microelectronics and Computer Technology Corp. (research).andO;Topic:     Holographic MemoryStorage EquipmentLasersDisk DrivesNew TechniqueProduct DevelopmentResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Steve Redfield. (portrait)Person:    Redfield, Steve (research).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>